import{f as e}from"index-939d0dd8.js"/*tpa=https://cdn.w3cbus.com/mdui/design-1/assets/index-939d0dd8.js*/;const o={a1:"Color in Material Design is inspired by bold hues juxtaposed with muted environments, deep shadows, and bright highlights.",a2:"Color Tool",a3:"Color palette",a4:"Color system",a5:"Usability",a6:"Themes",a7:'The <a href="https://material.io/color/" target="_blank">Color Tool</a> helps you create, share, and apply color palettes to your UI, as well as measure the accessibility level of any color combination.',a8:"Create color schemes",a9:"Create color schemes that include darker and lighter variations of your primary and secondary colors.",a10:"Test accessibility",a11:'Check if text is accessible on different-colored backgrounds, as measured using the <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/UNDERSTANDING-WCAG20/visual-audio-contrast-contrast.html" target="_blank">Web Content Accessibility Guidelines</a> legibility standards.',a12:"Preview your UI in color",a13:"Preview the look of your color scheme across a range of Material Design components, with editable HTML, CSS, or JavaScript in Codepen.",a14:"Color Tool",a15:"Create color palettes for your UI and test color accessibility",a16:"The color palette",a17:"This color palette comprises primary and accent colors that can be used for illustration or to develop your brand colors. They’ve been designed to work harmoniously with each other. The color palette starts with primary colors and fills in the spectrum to create a complete and usable palette for Android, Web, and iOS. Google suggests using the 500 colors as the primary colors in your app and the other colors as accents colors.",a18:"Themes enable consistent app styling through surface shades, shadow depth, and ink opacity.",a19:"Download color swatches",a20:"Choosing a color scheme",a21:"You can customize your app’s color scheme to match your brand colors. Alternatively, you can create an entirely new color scheme using the material design color palette.",a22:"When creating a color scheme:",a23:'Use the <a href="#color-color-tool">Color Tool</a> to create and apply palettes to your app',a24:"Ensure your app’s color usage meets accessibility standards, with sufficient contrast between elements",a25:"Expressing Brand in Material",a26:"A step-by-step guide to staying on-brand with Material Design",a27:"Material Design’s color system",a28:"In Material Design, a <strong>primary color</strong> refers to a color that appears most frequently in your app. A <strong>secondary color</strong> refers to a color used to accent key parts of your UI.",a29:"Using colors from the Material Design palette is optional.",a30:"This color scheme has a primary color, lighter and darker versions of that color, and a secondary color.",a31:"Beneath the region using the primary color, related information is colored with a lighter version of the primary color. The floating action button uses the secondary color to accent it.",a32:"This color scheme contains a primary color, plus darker and lighter versions of that color.",a33:"This primary color is applied to the toolbar and status bar, while also being used to accent the floating action button.",a34:"Primary color",a35:"A primary color is the color displayed most frequently across your app’s screens and components. It can also be used to accent elements, if you don’t have a secondary color.",a36:"To create contrast between elements, you can use lighter or darker tones of your primary color. The contrast between lighter and darker tones helps show division between surfaces, such as between the status bar and a toolbar.",a37:"This color scheme contains different tones of the primary color, for when lighter or darker contrast is needed.",a38:"Secondary Color",a39:"A secondary color is used to accent select parts of your UI. It can be complementary or analogous to your primary color, but it should not simply be a light or dark variation of your primary color. It should contrast with elements that surround it and be applied sparingly as an accent.",a40:"Secondary colors are best used for:",a41:"Buttons, floating action buttons, and button text",a42:"Text fields, cursors, and text selection",a43:"Progress bars",a44:"Selection controls, buttons, and sliders",a45:"Links",a46:"Headlines",a47:"Using a secondary color is optional. It’s not necessary if you use variations of your primary color to accent elements.",a48:"A secondary color scheme with varied tones.",a49:"Secondary color schemes do not have to be colorful. They only need to contrast with surrounding elements and be used sparingly throughout your UI.",a50:"Using color in your app",a51:"Large UI areas and elements should be colored with your primary color. A secondary color can be used to accent smaller areas. If you don’t have a secondary color, you can use your primary color instead for these areas.",a52:"The floating action button is accented using the secondary color, while the phone icon uses the primary color.",a53:"The switch uses the secondary color as an accent. The system bar uses the primary color, while the toolbar uses a darker variation of the primary color.",a54:"Use the primary color to accent elements, such as buttons or checkboxes.",a55:"Elements that appear rarely, such as alerts, should be distinct from other elements and not use your primary color.",a56:"To indicate that buttons and checkboxes are selected, use the primary color as an accent.",a57:"Your secondary color can be used on typical elements, such as buttons and links.",a58:"Secondary colors, and anything used to accent parts of the UI, should be used sparingly.",a59:"Use a secondary color for certain text, such as linked text.",a60:"Don’t use bright colors for body text, even if your primary or secondary colors are bright.",a61:'See the <a href="#color-color-tool">Color Tool</a> for more guidance about typographic legibility on color.',a62:"You can use your primary color as a link accent.",a63:"Use your primary or secondary color to emphasize select shorter text, such as headlines.",a64:"Use your secondary color for your primary action button.",a65:"Don’t use the secondary color for app bars, larger areas of color, or the floating action button if it rests on a background of that color.",a66:"Use a monochromatic color as an accent to let imagery and other colorful elements take prominence.",a67:"You can use your primary color in a different tone on elements that rest on top of a primary color region (like this floating action button).",a68:"Text fields and switches can use your secondary color as an accent.",a69:"Text selection can use your secondary color as an accent.",a70:"Alternative secondary colors",a71:"If your secondary color is too light or dark to sufficiently contrast with the background color, use a lighter or darker shade of the secondary color instead.",a72:"Use a different tone of your secondary color against backgrounds that are very light or very dark.",a73:"Don’t use a secondary color on top of a background if there is not enough contrast between the two colors.",a74:"Hierarchy",a75:"Hierarchy refers to organizing content according to different levels of importance. Color can convey how important some content is relative to other content.",a76:"For example, a brightly colored button on a colorless background makes that button stand out. Alternatively, colorless bars and buttons allow bright content to take prominence in a UI.",a77:"Bold color emphasizes the floating action button and the toolbar, giving prominence to message creation and navigation.",a78:"Colorless bars and buttons allow colorful content to take precedence, deemphasizing the status and navigation bars.",a79:"Meaning",a80:"Color may be used to communicate the meaning of various elements on a screen. A weather app may display colors that indicate current weather conditions, and a maps app may use color to show traffic conditions, with roads colored red or green.",a81:"A weather app uses color to signal the time of day.",a82:"A maps app uses color to signal traffic conditions.",a83:"State",a84:"Color can provide information about:",a85:"An element’s current state, such as if a button is enabled or disabled",a86:"An app or element’s change of state",a87:"Color that indicates a change of state should be noticeable, as subtle differences in color may be missed. It’s best to indicate a change of state in more than one way, such as displaying an icon or moving the location of an element.",a88:"The red color in the label and helper text indicate error messages.",a89:"The color changes from blue to red to indicate different states.",a90:"Contrast",a91:"Your app’s primary and secondary colors should ensure sufficient color contrast between elements so that all users can see and use your app.",a92:`To learn more about color, contrast, and accessibility design, read <a class="do-router" href="${e("/usability/accessibility.html")}">Material Design Accessibility</a>.`,a93:"In this UI, red signifies the time of day and green represents the foggy weather.",a94:"This is how users with deuteranopia (red/green color blindness) might see the UI shown to the left. They might not be able to see differences between text and other elements.",a95:"Additional affordances, beyond color, should be used to convey information.",a96:"Smaller text may be difficult to read for individuals with cataracts, for whom your UI may appear blurry. Elements without sufficient contrast get lost in the background.",a97:"To accommodate all users, offer enlarged text settings.",a98:"Text on backgrounds",a99:"Text should be legible on the background on which it appears. It is recommended that:",a100:"Dark gray text is used on light backgrounds",a101:"Light gray text is used on dark backgrounds",a102:"If your app has both light and dark themes, the text should be available in a contrasting color against each theme.",a103:"Legibility",a104:'Text that appears on colored backgrounds should be legible and meet accessibility standards. Both backgrounds and text must use colors and opacities that, when used together, meet these standards. The <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/UNDERSTANDING-WCAG20/visual-audio-contrast-contrast.html" target="_blank">Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG 2.0)</a> level AA requires a contrast ratio of 4.5:1 for normal text and a 3:1 ratio for large text.',a105:"Using opacity instead of shifting colors often creates better contrast and relative luminance. For example, gray text (#727272) becomes hard to read if the background color changes to magenta.",a106:"Shifting to gray instead of decreasing contrast on black often lowers the relative luminance, making typography unreadable.",a107:"Dark text on light backgrounds",a108:"The level of opacity used for text depends on whether your background is dark or light. For dark text on light backgrounds, apply the following opacity levels:",a109:"The <strong>most important text</strong> has an opacity of 87%",a110:"<strong>Secondary text</strong>, which is lower in the visual hierarchy, has an opacity of 54%",a111:"<strong>Text hints</strong> (such as text fields and labels) and <strong>disabled text</strong> have even lower visual prominence with an opacity of 38%",a112:"Dark text (#000000)",a113:"Opacity",a114:"Primary text",a115:"Secondary text",a116:"Disabled text, hint text",a117:"Dividers",a118:"White text on dark backgrounds",a119:"White text appearing on colored backgrounds should do so at an opacity of 100%.",a120:"The table relays relative levels of importance for white text on dark backgrounds.",a121:"Light text (#FFFFFF)",a122:"Icons and other elements",a123:"Elements like icons benefit from having a hex value of black or white at 38% opacity so that they work on backgrounds of any color.",a124:"Dark icons (#000000)",a125:"Active Icon",a126:"Inactive Icon",a127:"Light icons (#FFFFFF)",a128:"Colored text and backgrounds",a129:"Use colored text on colored backgrounds sparingly, limiting usage to important text elements. Colored text should be used to indicate importance and selective emphasis.",a130:'See the <a href="#color-color-tool">Color Tool</a> to determine if certain foreground colors used for typography meet accessibility standards against different background colors.',a131:"Use a contrasting color (such as your secondary color) on important text to contrast it against the background.",a132:"Avoid placing a large amount of colored text on colored backgrounds.",a133:"You can use a darker or lighter tone of color to create a monochrome, yet accentuated, look.",a134:"Don’t place low-contrast tones of the same color against each other. It’s difficult to read text with a low contrast against its background.",a135:"Themes let you apply a consistent tone to an app. The theme specifies the darkness of the surfaces, level of shadow, and appropriate opacity of ink elements. To promote greater consistency between apps, light and dark themes are available to choose from.",a136:"Download themes",a137:"Light theme",a138:"Status bar",a139:"App bar",a140:"Background",a141:"Cards/Dialogs",a142:"Light theme palette",a143:"UI application",a144:"Dark theme",a145:"Dark theme palette",a146:"UI application",a147:"Using the Material Theme",a148:"Customize the design to your brand identity.",a149:"Create Material Design color schemes with variations",a150:"Test Material Design accessibility on varied backgrounds",a151:"Preview Material Design color scheme in UI components",a152:"Material Design Logo",a153:"Material Design Download Icon",a154:"Google Design",a155:"Material Design color scheme: primary, secondary, and shades",a156:"Material Design: lighter primary color and secondary accent",a157:"Material Design color scheme with primary and variants",a158:"Material Design primary color for toolbar, status bar, and button",a159:"Material Design color scheme with varying primary tones",a160:"Material Design secondary color scheme with varied tones",a161:"Material Design: Use secondary colors for contrast sparingly",a162:"Material Design floating button in secondary color with phone icon",a163:"Material Design switch features secondary accent color",a164:"Material Design: Use primary color for selected buttons",a165:"Material Design secondary color for buttons and links",a166:"Use secondary color for links in Material Design",a167:"Avoid bright colors for body text in Material Design",a168:"Use primary color as link accent in Material Design",a169:"Emphasize text with primary/secondary colors in Material Design",a170:"Material Design: Use secondary color for primary button",a171:"Do not use secondary color for Material Design elements",a172:"Use a monochromatic accent for Material Design balance",a173:"Use Material Design primary color tones for overlay elements",a174:"Material Design: Use secondary color for text fields and switches",a175:"Text selection accent with secondary color in Material Design",a176:"Material Design: Use a contrasting tone for your secondary color",a177:"Material Design: Ensure contrast between background and colors",a178:"Material Design: Bold colors enhance action button and toolbar",a179:"Colorless Material Design bars enhance colorful content",a180:"Weather app with Material Design signals time of day",a181:"Material Design colors indicate traffic conditions on maps",a182:"Red label and helper text indicate Material Design errors",a183:"Material Design color changes from blue to red",a184:"Material Design UI with red for time and green for fog",a185:"Material Design UI view for users with color blindness",a186:"Material Design: Offer enlarged text for better readability",a187:"Material Design: Use opacity for better contrast",a188:"Material Design: Gray reduces contrast, harming readability",a189:"Material Design: Dark text opacity on light backgrounds",a190:"Material Design: Text importance for dark backgrounds",a191:"Use contrasting colors for important text in Material Design",a192:"Material Design: Avoid colored text on colored backgrounds",a193:"Use darker or lighter tones for a monochrome Material Design look",a194:"Material Design: Avoid low-contrast color combinations",a195:"Material Design Download Icon",a196:"Material Design light theme palette",a197:"Material Design UI Application",a198:"Material Design dark theme palette",a199:"Material Design UI application",a200:"Material Design Android Icon"};export{o as en};
